&gt; &gt; Kent Beck wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt; Elliotte,
&gt; &gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; &gt; Thank you for this perspective. You are absolutely right 
&gt; &gt; that if we had frequent releases the optimal strategy would 
&gt; &gt; be to conceal everything possible in the framework and open 
&gt; &gt; it up &quot;on demand&quot;. I don&#39;t see how to implement frequent 
&gt; &gt; releases with JUnit, however, since the IDE vendors bake 
&gt; &gt; JUnit into their offerings and we don&#39;t have any 
&gt; &gt; infrastructure to push updates. Perhaps I am just fussing 
&gt; &gt; about this, or there is a simple solution. I am open to suggestions.
&gt; &gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Most developers will not need to extend JUnit at all, no 
&gt; &gt; matter how many 
&gt; &gt; or which hooks you provide. If one does need an extra extension point 
&gt; &gt; that you decide is a good idea, then you can add it and make 
&gt; &gt; a release. 
&gt; &gt; The developers who need it can  fairly easily install it in 
&gt; &gt; their IDE or 
&gt; &gt; other framework.  As long as you don&#39;t actively change the 
&gt; &gt; published API 
&gt; &gt; or remove any pieces of it, the IDE should continue to work. So I 
&gt; &gt; wouldn&#39;t worry excessively about leaving something out.
